The problem is that fetching happens asynchronously in javascript - This means that your return statement is executed long before your network request is completed. Rather then returning the count straightaway, you can return a promise which is resolved to the number of fixtures once the network request is completed:

    numberOfFixtures(group) {
        // Returning a promise, not a value
        return http.get(&#39;fixture/group/&#39; + group.id)
            .then( result =&gt; {
                return result.length &gt; 0
                    ? result.length
                    : &#39;0&#39;;
            }).catch((error) =&gt; {
                console.error(error);
            });
        });
    }

